    "reasoning": "To implement the required state machine, I first analyze the state transition table. The states are encoded as A=2'b00, B=2'b01, C=2'b10, D=2'b11. The state transitions depend on both the current state and input 'in'. For each state, I determine the next state for both input values (0 and 1). Also, I determine the output for each state. Then, I implement the combinational logic using a case statement to map the current state and input to next state and output. Since this is purely combinational logic, I use 'always @(*)' without any sensitivity list.",
    "module": "module TopModule (\n    input  logic in,\n    input  logic [1:0] state,\n    output logic [1:0] next_state,\n    output logic out\n);\n\n    always @(*) begin\n        case (state)\n            2'b00: // State A\n                if (in) next_state = 2'b01; // Transition to B on input 1\n                else next_state = 2'b00; // Stay in A on input 0\n                out = 1'b0;\n            \n            2'b01: // State B\n                if (in) next_state = 2'b01; // Stay in B on input 1\n                else next_state = 2'b10; // Transition to C on input 0\n                out = 1'b0;\n            \n            2'b10: // State C\n                if (in) next_state = 2'b11; // Transition to D on input 1\n                else next_state = 2'b00; // Transition to A on input 0\n                out = 1'b0;\n            \n            2'b11: // State D\n                if (in) next_state = 2'b01; // Transition to B on input 1\n                else next_state = 2'b10; // Transition to C on input 0\n                out = 1'b1;\n            \n            default:\n                next_state = 2'b00;\n                out = 1'b0;\n        endcase\n    end\n\nendmodule"
}
